[`let`][1] returns the value of the specified function block.

So the logical explanation is that `&lt;1&gt;` returns `null`. In that case the whole expression `base64ToBmp(str)?.let { &lt;1&gt; }` becomes `null` and the right hand side of the elvis operator (i.e. `run { &lt;2&gt; }`) will be evaluated.

A very simplified way of reproducing it would be:

    &quot;foo&quot;?.let { print(&quot;&lt;1&gt;&quot;); null } ?: print(&quot;&lt;2&gt;&quot;)
    // Prints &lt;1&gt;&lt;2&gt;

Depending on your actual use case, [`apply`][2] or [`also`][3] (which both return the context object itself) might be suitable (note that for `apply` the object reference is passed as `this` instead of `it`):

    &quot;foo&quot;?.apply { print(&quot;&lt;1&gt;&quot;); null } ?: print(&quot;&lt;2&gt;&quot;)
    // Prints &lt;1&gt;

  [1]: https://kotlinlang.org/api/latest/jvm/stdlib/kotlin/let.html
  [2]: https://kotlinlang.org/api/latest/jvm/stdlib/kotlin/apply.html
  [3]: https://kotlinlang.org/api/latest/jvm/stdlib/kotlin/also.html

